<p align="center"><marquee>Got Dragon?</marquee></p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=coren>Coren</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/4/01 9:23:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=28.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wizard Familiars</span><hr size=1> Just saw this post and at first disregarded the idea as something that would really fit both the idea of the wizard class *and* Verant's balance between the classes, but after thinking about it a bit, some really interesting ideas are starting to flow. . .<br>
<br>
One concept for the wizard familiar - <br>
<br>
A high mana cost quote unquote &quot;pet&quot; (As in using 50% to 60% mana to cast), familiar stays with you upon zoning/logging (easy to work out with code, spell acts as a buff, if you zone/log in and buff is on, it checks for a familiar and if one isn't there it creates one).  Familiar then bestows whatever advantages that particular familiar should give, (including increased mana regen which I think should be standard, and the regen would be balanced by the initial casting cost and the risk of losing familiar).  Also the wizard should be able to switch between looking through the familiar's eyes and his own. (Might require an additional spell to implement this aspect, don't know how else it could be coded).<br>
<br>
If the familiar dies, caster takes certain amount of damage and loses a certain amount of mana from the system shock of losing it (familiars are mentally connected to their masters).<br>
<br>
If the familiar has any offensive ability at all, it should be magical in nature only (a familiar that casts a MR debuff would be pretty cool) and it's abilities could be set to go off when it's master goes into &quot;attack mode&quot;<br>
<br>
What's really neat about this is that the familiar's abilities could be tweaked and worked with to balance out the wizard class, and there are options for drawbacks to allow some counters to make room for some otherwise unbalancing abilities.  <br>
<br>
Got a lot more ideas stirring, but not all familiar related so might need to save them for another post.<br>
